    <title>Combined summary - Using a storage engine without UTXO-index</title>
    <updated>2023-06-11T23:57:34.478995+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2017-April/014048.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Tomas van der Wansem has developed a new approach to indexing for verifying the order of transactions in Bitcoin. The implementation uses a spend-tree to verify double spends by scanning against spent outputs, rather than using an index of unspent outputs. This method allows for better concurrency and performance when verifying individual inputs in parallel. Van der Wansem believes that this approach could lead to protocol improvements and should be considered an implementation detail.The new approach uses a Version3 store which doesn't use a spends table/index nor does it store any table of UTXOs. Instead, it uses the tx hash table augmented with 32 bits per output for spender height. The memory mapped files become in-memory hash tables and an opaque UTXO cache is implemented to limit paging on low memory machines. The downsides to the approach are higher than necessary storage space requirements but have resulted in faster performance without the storage cost or complexity disadvantages.Van der Wansem suggests that the minimal disk storage required in Bitcoin cannot be less than all the unspent outputs and that the UTXO data remains a significant long term resource cost, which is unavoidable without radical protocol changes such as TXO-proofs. However, during peak load block validation with pre-synced transactions, accessing storage can be minimized. In addition, the aggregate resource usage for users depends significantly on outputs rather than inputs in transactions in a block.There is discussion around whether application-layer caching is necessary given that allowing the operating system to use disk caching or memory map caching can be more effective. On lower memory systems, an explicit cache is beneficial and can be measured in production code by changing the cache limit and testing on various configurations. On high RAM systems, any cache is actually a de-optimization but on low RAM systems, it can prevent excessive paging.In a conversation between Gregory Maxwell and Tomas, it was discussed that Bitcoin Core software does not use mempool pre-validation as it can lead to hard-to-detect consensus faults and make all mempool code consensus-critical when it otherwise is not. Bitcrust does not need reorgs at all, making it less susceptible to these risks. The discussion also touched on whether splitting script validation and order validation introduces risks inherent to the protocol.Van der Wansem believes that his implementation could be used as a pluggable module for Bitcoin Core through its interface of queries, add_tx, and add_block with blobs and flags. However, due to the current tight coupling between network and storage on the Core's side, this may not be a simple task. He also expresses interest in building a Bitcrust networking component to bring a strong competitor to the market.In various email conversations and discussions on Bitcoin development forums, technical details and optimization strategies for Bitcrust and libbitcoin V2/V3 have been discussed. The use of PGP signatures for secure electronic communication and the importance of protocol/implementation separation has also been emphasized. A new approach to indexing for verifying transaction order using a spend-tree has been developed, and a network with multiple nodes maintaining a transaction index has been proposed to enable light node applications. However, there are still concerns about UTXO growth and long-term resource requirements, and limitations on 1-in-100-out transactions may need to be imposed for anti-Denial of Service purposes.Bitcrust's disk and memory usage cannot be accurately compared to Core's pruning mode, as it is not yet supported. Tomas questions Bitcrust's anti-DoS feature and proposes limiting the number of previous 1-in-100-out txs to prevent negative effects on performance. Mempool optimization is necessary to optimize disk and memory usage, but it is not yet supported. A new approach to indexing for verifying the order of transactions has been developed, which uses a spend-tree where spends are scanned against spent outputs instead of unspent outputs. This version3 store does not use spends table/index or any table of UTXOs. Gregory Maxwell questions whether a proposal for reversing the costs of outputs and inputs would be worth considering. Tomas introduced Bitcrust, which uses a transaction index that allows outputs to be looked up regardless of whether they have been spent or not. Tom Harding mentioned that network with many nodes maintaining a transaction index allows for light node applications that request peers to verify the existence and usage of Transaction Outputs (TXOs). However, this additional capability requires commitment structures like those proposed by Peter Todd in his stxo/txo commitment designs. The downsides to the approach are higher than necessary storage space requirement due to storing the indexing data required for correlate the spends, and higher than necessary validation complexity and cost in terms of computing the spent-ness (including spender height) of an output. Eric Voskuil suggested that to resolve the above two problems, the version3 store does not use a spends table/index, nor does it store any table of UTXOs.Bitcoin developers are exploring new approaches to indexing and verifying transactions in the cryptocurrency. Tomas van der Wan</summary>
